D-PA, thiol group containing the compound, easily interacts with Fe3+and forms complex with it. Hence, we attempted to develop fluorescence ‘turn on’ strategy for the determination of D-PA by using CDs-Fe3+ system as a probe. Thus, diminished fluorescence of a CDs-Fe3+ system could be recovered with the successive addition of D-PA. The sensitivity of the system was evaluated by adding different concentrations of D-PA solution in the range of 0–80 μg mL−1 into the CDs-Fe3+ system containing 1.84 mg mL−1 of CDs and 12 μg mL−1 of Fe3+ concentration. The almost 76.4% of fluorescence recovery of CD-Fe3+system in the presence of various concentrations of D-PA with slightly spectral shift of the emission band was observed [Fig. 6
                        ]. This amplification of the fluorescent intensity of CDs-Fe3+ with increasing concentration of D-PA was plotted as F/F0 against concentration of D-PA Where, F and F0 are the fluorescence intensity of CDs-Fe3+ system in the presence and absence of D-PA respectively at 430 nm and [Q] is the concentration of D-PA. The restoration of fluorescence intensity of CDs-Fe3+ system was not proportional to the entire concentration range of D-PA. The inset of Fig. 7
                        , shows linear calibration curve, allowing the quantification of D-PA in the range of 0–48 μg mL−1, which is wider linear detection range than previously reported method, with coefficient of regression (R2) is 0.9823 and slope of the curve 0.0293. The limit of detection (LOD) of present system was calculated by using 3σ/K equation where σ is a standard deviation and K is the slope of the linear curve and found to be 7.40 μg mL−1.
